(3) But as when violent winds, falling on a calm sea, turn it up MORAL· from its foundation, and mingle the sand with the waveS, so these passions assailing the soul turn all upside down, and dim the clearness of the mental sight, but especially does the mad desire of glory, For a contempt for money any one may easily attain, but to despise the honour that proceeds from the multitude, requires a great effort, a philosophie temper, a certain angelic soul that reaches to the very summit of heaven.

For there is no passion so tyrannical, so universally prevalent, in a greater or a less degree indeed, but still every where. How then shall we subdue it, if not wholly, yet in some little

part? By looking up to heaven, by setting God before our

eyeS, by entertaining thoughts superior to earthly things. Ima- gine, when thou desirest glory, that thou hast already attained

the toils and dangerS, yet be deprived of the fruits and rewards

the man is, and thou wilt see how ridiculous a thing is glory, that it is rather to be called shame.
